Alexander Kluber

Harmonic oscillator

The Fokker-Planck (Smoluchowski) equation for a 1D harmonic oscillator (V =
0.5*b*x**2) can be solved exactly. The timescales 

t_i = kT/((i - 1)*b*D)

Then I added a quickly varying potential that should slow the dynamics.
Theoretically, this should decrease the diffusion coefficient by

D = D_0*exp(-(dE/kT)**2)

where D_0 is some baseline diffusion coefficient, dE is the standard deviation
of the rough potential, and kT is the thermal energy scale. 

Interestingly, the ratio of each rough timescale t_i to corresponding smooth
timescale t_i_smooth only depends on dE/kT,

t_i/t_i_smooth = exp((dE/kT)**2)

(1) Zwanzig, R. Diffusion in a Rough Potential. Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. 1988,
85, 2029â€“2030.
